# Kernel ML language showcase

This document is valid Kernel ML (KML) source. It demonstrates **every syntax feature and expected behaviour** so you can see how the language works and how the compiler treats each construct. Compile it to HTML with the Rust WASM or TS pipeline to verify output.

---

# Headings

Headings use `#` at the start of a line. The default is level 1.

# One hash is level 1

We support **explicit level numbers** so numbering is stable: `#[n]` means "heading at level n".

#[1] First-level heading (same as #)

#[2] Second-level heading

#[3] Third-level heading

You can attach an **explicit ID** for cross-references and anchor links. Syntax: `#[n] Your title {#id}`. The ID is used as the HTML element id (and usually slugified for URLs).

#[1] Introduction {#intro}

#[2] Syntax overview {#syntax}

#[3] Block elements {#blocks}

---

# Paragraphs and line breaks

A **paragraph** is any run of non-blank lines. A **blank line** (or two newlines) ends the current paragraph and starts a new one.

This is one paragraph. It can span multiple lines as long as there is no blank line between them.

This is a second paragraph because there was a blank line above.

The **`\n` macro** expands to a single line break (`<br>`) and **does not** end the paragraph. So you can force a line break inside the same paragraph.

This paragraph has a line break\nright here, but it is still one paragraph.

The next paragraph starts after this sentence.

---

# Inline formatting: bold and italic

Use **one asterisk** for *italic* and **two asterisks** for **bold**. Delimiters are matched left-to-right; **longest delimiter wins** when both could apply. Bold and italic can nest: **bold with *italic* inside** and *italic with **bold** inside*. Unbalanced delimiters are a **compile-time error** (no recovery).

Example: *italic*, **bold**, and **bold with *italic* inside**.

---

# Inline code and code blocks

**Inline code** uses backticks. One backtick: `single`, or multiple to allow backticks inside: `` `code` with `` backticks ``. Nothing inside is parsed as markup (math, bold, etc. are suppressed).

Use a **fenced code block** for multi-line code. Opening fence: ``` optionally followed by a language tag. Closing fence: ``` at the **same indentation** as the opening fence. Internal lines can be indented; the compiler **trims** the same amount of leading indentation as the opening fence so you can indent code for readability.

```rust
fn main() {
    println!("Hello, Kernel ML!");
}
```

```text
If the opening fence is indented (e.g. inside a list),
  the closing fence must match that indent.
  Internal indentation is trimmed accordingly.
```

---

# Links and footnotes

**Links:** `[link text](url)`. The URL can contain literal parentheses; only the first matching `)` closes the URL, so trailing `)` in the URL are kept (author should encode if needed). Example: [example.com](https://example.com) and [URL with parens](https://example.com/path(a)b).

**Footnotes / citations:** `^[note text](url)`. They are **auto-numbered** in document order. Output is typically a superscript link to the note; a consolidated list of notes (bibliography) appears at the end. Example: a claim^[Source: [doc](https://example.com/doc)] and another^[Second note](https://example.com/two).

---

# Superscript and subscript

**Superscript:** `^{content}`. **Subscript:** `_{content}`. Braces must be **balanced**; you can escape braces as `\{` and `\}`. Nested formatting (e.g. bold or another sup inside) is **not** allowed—only the literal content.

Examples: x^{2}, y_{i}, and x^{2 + \{y\}} with an escaped brace.

---

# Inline math

Math is **not** parsed as Kernel ML; only TeX-style math is interpreted inside. Two forms:

- **Dollar:** `$...$` for inline math. Example: We have $x^2 + y^2 = z^2$ here.
- **Parens:** `\(...\)` for inline math. Example: Or \( \int_0^1 f(x)\,dx \) like this.

Document macros (e.g. `\n`) **do not** expand inside math; the pre-lexer finds math/code regions before macro expansion.

---

# Display math

**Display (block) math** is its own block. It inherits the **indentation** of its opening delimiter (e.g. when nested in a list). Two forms:

- **Double dollar:** `$$...$$` on its own lines or spanning lines.
- **Bracket:** `\[...\]`.

$$
\sum_{i=1}^{n} i = \frac{n(n+1)}{2}
$$

\[
\int_0^{2\pi} \sin^2 x\,dx = \pi
\]

---

# Lists

**Unordered lists:** line starts with `- ` (dash and space). **Ordered lists:** `=[a]`, `=[i]`, or `=[1]` for alphabetic, roman, or arabic. The **first nested item** sets the **file-wide indent unit** (e.g. 4 spaces); later inconsistent indentation is a compile-time error. At each depth, that many indent units define the "line start," so you can nest code blocks, display math, and sub-lists.

- first unordered item
- second item
    =[a] nested ordered (alphabetic)
    =[a] second at same depth
    =[1] arabic style
        - deeply nested bullet
        ```python
        def nested():
            return 42
        ```
        $$\sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{1}{2^k} = 2$$
    =[i] back to roman

---

# Frontmatter

If the **first line** is `---`, the parser reads until the next `---` as **frontmatter** (metadata). It is not rendered as body content; the emitter can use it for HTML `<meta>` or other metadata. Example at the top of this file.

---

# Parsing and compilation rules (summary)

=1. **Pre-lex:** Math and code regions are found first (code before math). No nesting.
2. **Macros:** Expanded top-to-bottom in normal text only; `\n` -> `<br>`. No expansion inside math/code.
3. **Blocks:** Frontmatter, headings, lists, code blocks, display math, then paragraphs. Lists and fences respect indentation.
4. **Inline:** Runs only inside paragraph/heading text. Code and math suppress further inline parsing.
5. **Errors:** Invalid or unmatched syntax fails compilation; no error correction.

---

# Raw HTML

Explicit HTML is allowed. No sanitisation; trust level equals raw HTML. (Not shown here to keep the sample safe; use with trusted source only.)
